ions of eminence -- tOn why we honor people for the achievements of their ancestors but not those of their progeny -- tOn why the progeny of illustrious people evince an elevated sense of entitlement and self-importance -- tOn whether it would be more consistent with the true order of things if all people were honored equally -- tOn different forms of divination -- tOn why some people dislike being addressed as "old man" while others relish it -- tOn why people take comfort from knowing they are not alone in their misfortune -- tOn the virtues of different nations, such as the Arabs, Byzantines, Persians, and Indians -- tOn why intelligent people are more susceptible to grief -- tOn why intrinsic merit and worldly fortune do not coincide -- tOn the meaning of coincidence -- tOn the nature of compulsion and choice -- tOn the reason for the wanderlust experienced by certain people -- tOn why people desire knowledge, and on the benefits of knowledge -- tOn why people and other animals respond so powerfully to certain kinds of sounds and musical effects -- tOn why older people are more liable to hope; on the meaning of "hope" and related terms -- tOn why women are more jealous than men; on the nature and moral status of jealousy -- tOn why more people die young than die old -- tOn why people seek likenesses -- tOn why we find it easier to represent extreme ugliness in our imagination than exquisite beauty -- tOn why sudden joy affects people so violently -- tOn why we experience states of suffering more intensely than states of well-being -- tOn why seeing someone laughing causes others to laugh -- tOn why human beings are so attached to the world despite the misfortunes and suffering they experience in it -- tOn why people say the world would fall to ruin if it weren't for fools -- tOn the anxiety experienced by people who have something to hide -- tOn why we are more likely to heed a preacher who practices what he preaches -- tOn why Arabs and non-Arabs declare their pedigrees in times of war -- tOn why people distinguish between different kinds of air, water, and earth, but not different kinds of fire -- tOn why people feel happier when they unexpectedly obtain something they weren't seeking than when they obtain what they were seeking -- tOn why fine edifices fall to ruin when left uninhabited -- tOn why men of sublime character beget knaves -- tOn why our longing for home grows more intense the nearer we come to it 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aQuestions and answers from two great philosophersWhy is laughter contagious? Why do mountains exist? Why do we long for the past, even if it is scarred by suffering? Spanning a vast array of subjects that range from the philosophical to the theological, from the philological to the scientific, The Philosopher Responds is the record of a set of questions put by the litterateur Abu Hayyan al-Tawhidi to the philosopher and historian Abu 'Ali Miskawayh. Both figures were foremost contributors to the remarkable flowering of cultural and intellectual life that took place in the Islamic world during the reign of the Buyid dynasty in the fourth/tenth century. The correspondence between al-Tawhidi and Miskawayh holds a mirror to many of the debates and preoccupations of the time and reflects the spirit of rationalistic inquiry that animated their era. It also provides insight into the intellectual outlooks of two thinkers who were divided as much by their distinctive temperaments as by the very different trajectories of their professional careers. Alternately whimsical and tragic, wondering and brooding, trivial and profound, al-Tawhidi's questions provoke an interaction as interesting in its spiritedness as in its content. This new edition of The Philosopher Responds is accompanied by the first full-length English translation of this important text, bringing this interaction to life for the English reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Okt 2020) 0aAuthors, ArabyTo 1258vCorrespondence. 0aIslamic philosophyvEarly works to 1800. 0aPhilosopherszIrany10th centuryvCorrespondence. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aMiskawayh, Abū ʿAlī, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMontgomery, James E.1 aOrfali, Bilal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPomerantz, Maurice A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVasalou, Sophia08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071028140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479865444423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479865444.jpg  a978-3-11-071028-1  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK